text: "Cosmo"-Haaronlineshop (Rock your hair Shampoo, Tangle Angel Haarbürste)  Hallo meine Süßen.  Ich war auf der Suche nach neuen und für mich ausgefallenen Haarprodukten, die man so nicht in der "normalen Drogerie" findet. Der Onlineshop "Cosmo" ist ein Großhändler für professionellen Friseurbedarf. Was macht den Haar-Onlineshop "Cosmo" so einzigartig?: "Cosmo beliefert internationale Friseursalons mit Profiartikeln. Bei Cosmo im Onlineshop findet ihr ein riesiges Sortiment an verschiedenen Stylings und Haarpflegeprodukten.""Für jedes Haar findet ihr im Onlineshop die entsprechenden Pflegeprodukte."   Bei Cosmo findet ihr Marken wie Babyliss, Beautyblender, Cloud Nine, EVO, GHD, Goldwell, Invisibobble, Jack Dean, KMS California, Londa, L’Oréal, Londa, Matrix, Paul Mitchell, Redken, Rock your hair,Schwarzkopf, Sebastian, System Professional, Tangle Teezer, Tigi, Volume Hair,Wella. Ich habe in dem Onlineshop zwei wirklich interessante Produkte gefunden, die ich getestet habe. Ich habe mir einmal ein Shampoo von Rock your hair und eine tollen Tangle Teezer in Form von Engelsflügeln ausgesucht: Das "Rock your hair" Big Hair Rocks Shampoo:  Dieses pink-neonfarbende "Rock your hair" Shampoo hat mich alleine schon von der Farbe und der Flaschenform sehr angesprochen. Ich habe ehrlich gesagt noch keine Erfahrungen mit dieser Marke gemacht. Ich habe bisher immer nur die normalen Shampoos aus der Drogerie genutzt (wie z.B.von Balea, von John Frieda, Alverde, usw.)Herstellerversprechen: -Dieses "Rock your hair" Shampoo soll feuchtigkeitsspendend sein und dem Haar mehr Volumen geben. Es ist zudem sulfat-und parabenfrei.  -Ideal als Farbschutz für coloriertes Haar und auch für keratinbehandeltes Haar geeignet." Preis: 14, 95€ (momentan aber auf 11,21€ reduziert).   Das Shampoo sieht von der Form wie eine "Aladdin"Flasche. Die Flasche ist sehr dünn und liegt aufgrund der gewölbten Form in der Mitte gut in der Hand. Ich finde dieses kleine Strassstein-Herzchen an dem oberen Teil der Flasche richtig süß. Das Strass-Herzchen ist ein wirklicher Hingucker. Das "Rock your hair" Shampoo verfügt über einen weißen Deckel mit einer kleinen, aufklappbaren Öffnung. Die Öffnung ist wirklich sehr klein, sodass nicht allzu viel Produkt aus der Flasche hervorkommt. Der Duft des Shampoos gefällt mir richtig gut. Es riecht sehr blumig und erinnert mich an einen sehr hochwertigen Duft. Das Shampoo selbst ist rosa-weiß. Die Textur des Duschgeles ist typisch flüssig und leicht gelartig. Es lässt sich sehr einfach und gleichmäßig ins Haar auftragen und einmassieren. Eine kleine Menge in der Hand reicht vollkommen aus. Das Shampoo ist für mich auch sehr ergiebig. Ich habe es sehr oft benutzt und ich habe noch nicht mal die Hälfte des Shampoos leer bekommen.  Nachdem das Shampoo auf das Haar gegeben hat, entfaltet sich auch schon der sehr angenehm-blumige Duft. Beim Verteilen und Einmassieren schäumt das Shampoo sehr leicht auf. Nachdem ich das Shampoo ins Haar einwirken lassen habe, konnte ich ohne Probleme das Shampoo ausspülen. Es blieben selbstverständlich keine Rückstände im Haar zurück. Nach dem Ausspülen hat sich mein Haar ganz normal angefühlt. Es fühlte sich schon sehr glatt an. Bei manchen Shampoos hatte ich ja das schonmal,dass sich das Haar sehr klebrig angefühlt hat. Das war bei diesem Shampoo aber nicht der Fall. Meine Haare konnte ich gut nach der Anwendung mit dem "Rock your hair" Shampoo föhnen und stylen. Ich hatte keine Knoten in der Haare und habe auch keine Haare durch dieses Shampoo verloren. Das Gefühl der Haare gefiel mir auch richtig gut. Meine Haaren fühlten sich weich und geschmeidig an. Volumen hat dieses Shampoo bei mir leider nicht geschaffen, da sie eher glatter waren als vorher. Der Duft des Shampoos blieb für einige Zeit in meinem Haar zurück. Meine Haare sind auch nicht schneller fettiger durch dieses Shampoo geworden. Die "Tangle Angel" (Haarbürste in Silber):   Diese süße Tangle Angle Haarbürste in Form von Engelsflügeln hat es mir richtig angetan. Als ich sie im Onlineshop gesehen habe, musste ich sie einfach ausprobieren. Das Design ist wirklich zauberhaft. Ich selbst habe noch keine Erfahrungen mit solchen Tangle-Teezer ähnlichen Haarbürsten gemacht. Diese Haarbürste gibt es in 2 weiteren Farbvarianten (Schwarz und Pink-Weiß). Herstellerversprechen: "Seidig glattes Haar - wie von Engelshand.  Tangle Angel besänftigt wirres Haar wirksam und sieht dabei noch verdammt gut aus!  Die Magie entspringt der engelhaften Formgebung und der innovativen Technik. Die speziell entwickelten Borsten führen zu der Flexibilität, wirres Haar auf sanfteste Weise in Bestform zu bringen. Die Tangle Angel ist antistatisch, antibakteriell und hitzebeständig. Anzuwenden in nassem und trockenem Haar und auch für Haarverlängerungen geeignet." Preis: 18,90€ (momentan auf 14,17€ reduziert)  Die Haarbürste hat nicht nur ein auffälliges Engelflügel-Design, sondern auch sehr interessante, schwarze Borsten. Die Borsten sind bei dieser Haarbürste unterschiedlich hoch angeordnet. Die Borsten in der Mitte sind viel niedriger angerichtet als die Äußeren. Diese Idee finde ich gelungen. Die inneren Borsten kommen sehr gut an die feinen Haare und an die Kopfhaut und die äußeren Borsten trennen die einzelnen Haare gut. Sie wirkt von der Form sehr stabil und sie liegt mit dem langen silbernen Griff sehr gut in der Hand. Meine Haare lassen sich mit dieser Haarbürste sehr gut durchkämmen. Ich habe nicht das Gefühl gemacht, dass sehr viele Haare mit dieser Bürste herausgerissen worden sind. Klar lässt sich Haarausfall mit keiner Haarbürste vermeiden.   Ich finde es gut,dass diese Haarbürste antibakteriell und hitzebeständig ist. Ich habe diese Haarbürste im trockenen und nassen Zustand bei meinen Haaren angewendet. Beim Durchkämmen von meinen nassen Haaren nach dem Duschen war ich positiv überrascht, wie gut sich meine Haare mit dieser Haarbürste durchkämmen ließen. Ich habe nach dem Duschen manchmal sehr leichte Knoten. Dieses klei

Ted Cruz Vs. Margaret Sanger’s Portrait Senator Ted Cruz and two dozen Republican Congressmen, led by Representative Louie Gohmert, have a problem with Margaret Sanger’s head. Sanger, who helped found the American Birth Control League, the organization that became Planned Parenthood, is represented in the National Portrait Gallery, one of the Smithsonian museums, by a bronze bust. It is currently part of an exhibition called the “Struggle for Justice,” which records, through the faces of those involved, this country’s slow movement toward civil rights. Earlier this month, the legislators sent a letter to the museum which describes Sanger as a racist who was bent on carrying out a genocide, the “extermination” of black Americans—a charge for which, as at least some of them surely know, there is no sound historical basis—and said that her bust should “not be displayed in or on any Smithsonian operated property.” Gohmert, in a press release that accompanied the letter, went further, saying that the bust should be “removed” from the collection. Apparently, Sanger’s face is too much to tolerate within federally funded walls, even in a back room. “It happens during election cycles,” Kim Sajet, the director of the National Portrait Gallery, told me by phone, referring to complaints about Sanger, though she said it does not usually come in the form of a letter from Congressional leaders. Last week, Sajet wrote back to the Republicans, stating that the museum would keep Sanger, on the ground that excluding her “would deny the public and future generations insight on an important chapter in American history.” Sajet is waiting to see what comes next from Cruz and Gohmert. The museum has private funders but gets a good part of its budget from Congress, and so it has certain vulnerabilities. But Sajet said that she saw no way for the museum to be what it was meant to be and accede to such requests. “There’s no moral test to be in the National Portrait Gallery,” she said. “If we did that there’d be nobody on the walls.” Indeed, although the bust of Sanger may look like something in a Hall of Fame, that’s not the idea of the National Portrait Gallery. It’s not a pantheon or shrine. It’s a place to take a look at the faces of the defining characters in the nation’s history. For example, there are portraits not only of Abraham Lincoln and John Wilkes Booth, but of Laura Keene, the actress who starred in “Our American Cousin,” the play that Lincoln was watching when Booth shot him; Keene was a highly regarded performer, and a good reason for Lincoln to get out of the White House that night. (Some of his blood ended up on her costume.) The Founding Fathers are there, but so is Samuel Seabury, the clergyman who admonished New Yorkers to just listen to the King. Benedict Arnold, the traitor, and Roger Taney, who wrote the Dred Scott decision, are in the collection. Sanger has been accused of being a eugenicist in the mode of Josef Mengele, but the presence of Henry Ford and Charles Lindbergh, who were actually deeply compromised by their anti-Semitism and ties to Nazism, has not attracted the same complaints. Nor should it: this is not a beauty pageant but a dramatis personae—at times very dramatic. There’s Josephine Baker and Michael Jackson, Nikola Tesla and Bill Gates, Generals Patton and Schwarzkopf, the boxer Jack Johnson (known as the Galveston Giant) and George Steinbrenner. There are dozens of slaveholders. Presidents get in automatically. That’s the easy explanation, anyway—to not exactly defend Sanger, but to note that if Al Capone (also in the collection) is O.K., then she should be, too. It’s also an answer that Kim Sajet finds unsatisfying and even frustrating. “There are bad guys, we know what they’ve done,” Sajet said. “Margaret Sanger is being demonized for a lot of things she didn’t do.” She was “not perfect,” Sajet pointed out, but nor was she a “eugenicist leader.” (As Jill Lepore, writing in The New Yorker, explained, “At one point, the American Birth Control League discussed a merger with the American Eugenics Society. But Sanger was a socialist, which often put her at odds with the eugenicists, and with her own organization.” Lepore also quotes Martin Luther King, Jr.,’s assessment that “there is a striking kinship between our movement and Margaret Sanger’s early efforts.”) Sanger solicited money for her cause from eugenicists. She also worried about overpopulation, and some of what she had to say about that is unattractive, such as when she suggested that it would be better if poor families had fewer children, and “imbeciles” none at all. But she did not, despite frequent Republican charges to the contrary—from Ben Carson, among others—found the forerunner of Planned Parenthood in order to prevent black children from being born. An earlier era’s complaint about Planned Parenthood was that it didn’t put enough clinics in black neighborhoods or work hard enough to provide service to those communities. In 1939, Sanger wrote a letter to a colleague stressing the importance of working with black ministers in the South to counter what she makes clear would be false theories about what the group was doing: “We do not want word to go out that we want to exterminate the Negro population and the minister is the man who can straighten out that idea if it ever occurs to any of their more rebellious members.” The first part of this sentence, without the phrases that make her meaning clear, is what is Cruz, Gohmert, and their cohort quoted as proof that Sanger’s mission was one of “extermination,” in a way that can only be called false. (There have been objections from the left, too, to words like “rebellious”; at the same time, Sanger fought with her own organization over her belief that it should hire more black public-health professionals, rather than relying on white experts.) How to fix your thinning hair First things first, if you’ve got thinning hair remember you’re not alone. About 70 per cent of all men will suffer from male pattern baldness (or “androgenic alopecia”) in their lifetime. And that’s not taking into account the guys who might lose their hair for other reasons, whether that be old age, stress or even from wearing that tightly tied man bun for too long. Losing your hair is nothing to be ashamed of — however the things some men do to try and disguise it are. If you don’t want to spend your life looking like Donald Trump, it’s best to embrace your follicular situation and work with what you’ve got. Remember, no man has ever got laid because of their combover.
However, we’re not suggesting you should immediately reach for the razor and shaving foam as soon as you see a few extra hairs in the plughole. There are plenty of tricks to disguise thinning hair — all you have to do is invest in the right products and a haircut that makes the most of any follicular failings.
Here we break down the action plan you need to follow, with a little expert advice from the man behind cool London barbershop Joe & Co., Joe Mills.

Add textureMale pattern baldness comes in two main forms:
1. Thinning from the front area
2. Thinning from the crown
Your options will depend on this as it will decide on what style you should go for. If you have less hair at the crown try to keep a little more length through the front. If you are thinning in the front you may decide you want to wear it longer around the back and sides – just be careful not to let the sides get too long and thick as it will serve to emphasise the discrepancy in thickness.
Your hair needs to have volume and texture to it so it doesn’t sit flat to your head – this gives it the appearance of being fuller. Whichever area you’re thinning in, ask your barber to texturise and remove weight from the rest of your hair – this will help the thicker areas match up with the thinner areas and will give you more options when styling.
And remember to take things short — shorter hair will appear thicker. Anything longer than a max of 3.5 inches will only make your thinner areas more noticeable.

A hat or a man bun can make things worseTwo classic responses that you might have to covering up your thinning hair: a) grow it out so you can pull it back all back over the the bald area into a man bun or b) keep the sides longer, but simply get into wearing hats to cover up the top. Both of these quick fixes could be actually speeding up your hair loss. Not only will scraping your hair backwards into a man bun put undue strain on your remaining hair, but wearing hats for long periods of time will starve your hair follicles of oxygen, clogging them up and preventing them producing the oils hair needs to grow.

Only go for the full shave when you’re ready“Go for the full shave when you feel that it’s the look you want, not because you feel that’s the only way to go,” says Joe Mills. “Personally I think that this isn’t down to how thin your hair is and I am constantly advising clients that there other options. A short scissor crop with added texture (finger width or slightly longer) works really well on thinning hair, and gives a great look without being too brutal a change.”

Invest in the right hair productsThe last thing your thinner hair needs are products that weigh it down. Go into your grooming cabinet and throw out any thick pastes, heavy conditioners or gloopy gels and invest in lighter alternatives. Start with a cleansing conditioner, then style using sea salt spray, volumising powder and hairspray — or perhaps a specially formulated, light paste if you need a little extra control. Remember, it’s all about adding texture without adding bulk to your barnet. Here’s our selection of the best products for thinning hair for men on the market…

Aveda Invati Man Shampoo and Scalp RevitalizerAs conditioner can add unnecessary weight to your hair, Aveda has pioneered a new technique for cleansing and thickening your hair as a part of your morning routine. The exfoliating shampoo cleans out any blockages in your hair follicles (encouraging stronger hair to grow), then the Scalp Revitalizer helps to thicken your hair when massaged in post-shower.

Schwarzkopf Osis+ Dust It Mattifying PowderAn easy way to add texture without adding weight is by sprinkling on some volumising powder. Rubbing this in not only controls your hair, but will also make it appear thicker without the need for wax or gel.

Schwarzkopf Color Ultime Hair Dye Would you believe that I’ve never dyed my hair at home before? Yup, I never have… until now! When Schwarzkopf approached me about their new spring Colour Ultime hair collection, I decided to give at home hair dying a go and also lighten my hair up a bit for the summer!
The shade I chose was 3.8- velvet brown.
The box and package of the hair dye was pretty standard, just like any other boxed hair dye. It also shows you how the hair colour would look on you depending on how dark/light your hair is.
My package also came with an accompaniment of shampoo and conditioner for coloured hair. I used to dye my hair quite often back in high school/early university years. Whenever my hair was dyed, I made sure to always use shampoo for coloured hair.
This makes a great difference in how the hair colour turns out, and how long the colour lasts. So, I definitely recommend getting a  shampoo for coloured hair if you plan on dying your hair!
The Schwarzkopf Colour Ultime hair dye came with a clear and detailed instruction sheet, applicator bottle with developer lotion already inside, the squeeze bottle of the hair dye, gloves, and after care hair elixir.
Set up is really easy, you just squeeze the hair dye into the applicator bottle. Then, shake the bottle vigourously until the developer lotion and hair dye are mixed well.
Since it was my first time trying at home hair dye, I enlisted the help of my trusted and experienced friend to make sure the process went as smooth as possible! I definitely recommend having someone to help, as it would be a bit more difficult to evenly distribute the dye throughout your hair yourself.
I also recommend dying your hair in an old tshirt, just in case you accidentally get hair dye on it. Or, you could wear a garbage bag/plastic poncho thingy to protect your clothes as well. Since I had my friend helping me, it was a very clean and fast process!
I won’t go super detailed into the application process, but it was very smooth. We were both really surprised at how good the Schwarzkopf dye smelled, as were preparing for the familiar chemical smell of hair dye. There was a small hint of it, but definitely not as strong as at the salon, or with other at home hair dyes my friend had used in the past.
After evenly distributing the hair dye, your hair should look something like this! I then left it in my hair for 30 minutes, which was the recommended time.
Thirty minutes later, I washed my hair out with warm water (they recommended warm water) and used the shampoo and conditioner as well! Again, the shampoo and conditioner smelled very pleasant with a hint of coconut. As previously mentioned, the box comes with the after care elixir, which is a deep conditioning treatment. There is enough in the tube for 3-4 uses, depending on how long/thick your hair is.

Ta-daaaa! Here is the final result! My hair is naturally pretty dark, so I wasn’t sure if the hair dye would show up or not. But, I’m glad it did! In the sunlight, it is more noticeable though.
I love the new lighter colour and it is definitely fitting as we get into summer! If you’re planning on dying your hair at home, I recommend giving Schwarzkopf a try!
Thanks for reading,
Carmen
Media samples featured. Opinions are own.

Schwarzkopf Schauma Roots to Tips Conditioner Review Hello IMBBians,
Conditioning is needed when you want to keep your mane nourished and fabulous-looking. Today I will be reviewing the conditioner I picked up as a pair along with the shampoo as somewhere I still believe that same variants show great results than using 2 different ones. So read on to know more about Schwarzkopf Schauma Roots to Tips Conditioner.


Price: €2.19 for 250ml
What the company claims:
The silicone-free formula with Pink Grapefruit & Avocado-Milk cares for your lengths and tips without weighing down the hair.
• Strengthens the hair structure and targeted repair.
• For shiny & supple hair, without over-treating.
• For perfectly cared hair with up to 3X better combing ability.
Ingredients:

My Experience with Schwarzkopf Schauma Roots to Tips Conditioner:
I had purchased this conditioner long before I switched to hair masks. I picked this as the shampoo and conditioner was tailor made for my hair type and it was silicone free!
The colour combination of the conditioner bottle comes from its ingredients: pink grapefruit and avocado milk. The bottle is sleek and has a silver flip cap which is quite good. There is no leakage and is perfect for travelling. The conditioner is creamy and thick and smells fruity and pleasant. The fragrance however doesn’t last long.

When the conditioner is rinsed off, you can feel the smoothness of the hair. A pea size drop is enough for shoulder length hair. After drying, the hair has no tangles and is easily manageable. The combing is easier as per the claim. Most of the times, I just run my fingers through my hair and it is fixed! The conditioner also doesn’t alter the hair texture. While the conditioner does make hair soft and smooth, there is no shine.
The normal healthy lustre stays but it is nothing great. The product doesn’t weigh down your hair and doesn’t leave any residue and it also adds a natural bounce. I was able to go straight 3 days without washing my hair and my hair was still soft and there was no oiliness. The ends of the hair were also well nourished and were looking healthy. However, this works when both the shampoo and conditioner are used together, if not, there are limited results. So summing up:
Pros of Schwarzkopf Schauma Roots to Tips Conditioner:
• Travel friendly.
• Pleasant fragrance.
• Makes hair soft, smooth, nourished and manageable.
• Hair gets easily combed; you can run your fingers and get the hair ready after a bath.
• Doesn’t weigh down the hair.
• Doesn’t make the scalp oily and makes hair look a little bouncy.
• Silicone free, so no build up.
• Effectively priced.

Cons of Schwarzkopf Schauma Roots to Tips Conditioner:
• Has to be used along with shampoo for the desired results.
IMBB Rating: 5/5
Would I Recommend the Schwarzkopf Schauma Roots to Tips Conditioner? 
Yes!

Batiste Light and Blonde Hint of Color Dry Shampoo Review Hello lovely ladies,
Seeing so many dry shampoo reviews from Saloni reminded me that I too have a dry shampoo with me, not yet reviewed, so here goes, let’s find out more about it.

Product Details (From the Website):
Batiste refreshes your hair between washes, leaving it feeling gorgeously clean and fresh with added body and texture. No water required! With a range of products to choose from, Batiste makes every day a fabulous hair day. Example Usage Occasions – On the days between washes to quickly refresh your hair. In the morning before work. If you are running short of time or just want and extra half an hour in bed.  Blissful blondes! Keep your hair full of body and beauty with our tinted dry shampoo, designed especially for you and your lusciously light locks.  A hint of color complements light and blonde hair tones and helps blend in root re-growth of colored, tinted or bleached hair. A quick burst revitalizes hair, leaving it feeling clean and fresh. No need to worry about skipping a shampoo.

How To Use:
Shake can vigorously and spray Batiste into the roots, keeping the nozzle 30 cm from hair. Massage through with fingertips. Brush hair and style as usual.
Price:
US 8.99/INR 950

My Experience with Batiste Light and Blonde Hint of Color Dry Shampoo:
I have dry hair with an oily scalp. Generally, they have a will of their own. With the combination of Livon and Schwarzkopf Color Freeze spray conditioner (reviewed earlier), I try to get some semblance out of them.

This was my first dry shampoo. Why did I pick up “A hint of colour – Light and Blonde?”Well, honestly because the regular one was sold out and since I have golden streaks in my hair, I thought why not give this a shot instead.
Honestly, first up, I didn’t quite like it too much, which may well be because I wasn’t using it correctly. I was barely spraying any because I was too scared of using “yet another” chemical on my scalp, which was anyway struggling with hair fall. Well, if you don’t use the product right, you can’t get the desired results, right?

So, I gathered enough courage and started using it more liberally. My hair is very fine ad the scalp gets really oily by day 2-3, sometimes, even earlier in this humid weather of Mumbai. This dry shampoo works very well. You spray it on your scalp and the roots of your hair, and then rub it in. The product disappears, leaving non-greasy hair behind.

A couple of things to note here:

There is a strong fragrance. It does not bother me but you have to take that into account. The smell dissipates fairly quickly.
Post application and rubbing off, the hair instantly loses its greasiness. It is so fantastic!
However, the texture of the hair post using this is not the same as that post having a head bath. Post head bath, my hair feels softer and lighter. Whereas, post application of this dry shampoo, my hair definitely feels a bit….crunchy!! It kind of builds a bit of volume to the hair. This may or may not be liked by all. Personally, I am okay with it.
The most important aspect – the color tint of the spray. The spray is definitely yellow tinted since it’s for light and blonde hair. However, post rubbing, the color just dissipates. There is no tint, color, anything left behind. So, if someone is thinking of using it to cover their grey roots with a gold tint, it’s not gonna work. Honestly, I don’t quite comprehend the reason for doing a tinted version since the color anyways dissipates.

To sum this up for you:
Pros of Batiste Light and Blonde Hint of Color Dry Shampoo:

Functional packaging; however, not ideal for travel. The normal bottle is too big to carry.
Strong fresh fragrance.
Absorbs oil instantly- leaving the hair fresh.
Gives volume to the hair.
Functional nozzle.
Leaves no residue on hair.
Does not weigh hair down.
No need to wash off – well, that the whole logic, right?

Cons of Batiste Light and Blonde Hint of Color Dry Shampoo:

The color tint is rendered ineffective post rubbing off the product, so the company’s claim of “helps blend in root re-growth of colored, tinted or bleached hair” is not really true.
The effect lasts for just that day.

IMBB Rating:
It’s definitely a good dry shampoo, but there is no need to opt for the “Light and Blonde” variant. You might as well go with the transparent normal option. However, if you don’t get the normal one, you can totally take this without worrying about it staining your hair golden or something!  Dry shampoo is a real game changer, especially for girls like us who have long hair for whom finding time to wash and dry the hair is such a pain. Having said that, I would not recommend it to be used on a daily basis.

6 Hacks for Covering Your Greys at Home Too impatient to book a salon appointment and too vain to let my greys take over, I have often tried to colour my hair at home. The result? More dye on the bathroom tiles than on my snowy strands. To master DIY dyeing, I invited Toronto hairstylist and The Social regular Caitlin Cullimore into my powder room. “In the ’80s, home hair dye smelled and the shades were weak,” Cullimore told me. “Now the main difference versus salon colour is in the hands of the person applying it.” So, as my toddler sat on my lap pawing at her comb, Cullimore broke down my path to success.
Colouring at home is fine if you’re using a shade that’s similar to your natural colour
If you want pastel ombré or Marilyn blonde, Cullimore suggests seeing your favourite colourist. If you want to cover greys, brighten up your hair and add shine, then box dye is for you.
Look for a permanent dye that guarantees 100 per cent grey coverage. Get two boxes if your hair is thick or longer than shoulder length
“It’s still a way better deal than going to a salon,” points out Cullimore. Use the index on the box to get a sense of the shade and don’t be afraid to mix two adjoining shades from the range for a custom blend. Just make sure to mix the entire contents of both bottles for an even hue.
Make sure the hair is truly saturated
Use the tail of a wide-tooth comb to create small sections, then start applying the colour at the roots. Don’t rush this is the pivotal step. Then massage the colour in and comb the remainder of the dye through the lengths.
Prevent stains
Apply a thin layer of petroleum jelly around your hairline and ears. Wipe any fresh drips away with a towel dampened with water and your go-to face wash. If you find any pesky staining after the fact, your regular makeup remover should help fade it, says Cullimore.
Start the clock when you’re finished applying the colour
“Hair colour times out, as long as you’re not using a product with bleach, so it won’t damage your hair or get lighter,” explains Cullimore. For regrowth, cover your roots and let the product sit for about 20 minutes before applying the remainder to your lengths. Then rinse, rinse, rinse. The water must run totally clear or you’ll risk ruining your towels and pillowcases.
DIY your dye a week before your big event
“It’s still fresh but the colour has time to settle,” says Cullimore. Then, invest in a shampoo with a UV filter and wash your hair as infrequently as possible. As for my hair? The colour was as rich as the Chardonnay I poured to raise a toast to my new look—and the fact that I had more time and money to spend on the things that matter, like an afternoon with my son. And wine. Mostly, in that order.

Schwarzkopf Keratin Color in Cappuccino, $13, Walmart. Sephora Tidy detangling comb, $10, sephora.ca

Proste czy kręcone? Cześć!Wczoraj susząc włosy o mało nie dostałam zawału- suszarka przestała działać. Niestety nie umiem się obejść bez tego urządzenia. Gdybym pozostawiła swoje włosy aby same podeschły miałabym istne siano na głowie. Pomijam fakt, że zanim przestałyby być mokre upłynęłoby 5 godzin :) Szlag by mnie trafił. Na szczęście po chwili się włączyła. (Rzecz jasna, nie odbierzcie tego źle. Chciałabym mieć tylko takie problemy hehe :) )Zdałam sobie sprawę, że moja suszarka swoje latka już ma i najwyższa pora zacząć rozglądać się za czymś innym. Sięgnęłam dziś po moje ulubione termoloki. Zawinęłam włosy, odkurzyłam dom, ściągnęłam wałki i gotowe! Uwielbiam takie szybkie rozwiązania.Po raz pierwszy użyłam modelującego żelu ELASTIN+ FLEX CONTROL w sprayu z SCHWARZKOPF. Chyba błąd zrobiłam, że postanowiłam pryskać każde pasmo z osobna- ciężko mi było w nie trafić :P Następnym razem będę aplikować warstwowo. Działanie samego żelu jest jak najbardziej ok. Loki są utrwalone, choć wiadomo po jakimś czasie trochę się wyprostowały- jednak ja właśnie taki efekt najbardziej lubię.Cała fryzura do wieczora świetnie się trzymała. Moje włosy mają skłonność do strączkowania i często kiedy je kręciłam to po paru godzinach zwisały strąki loków. Nie wygląda to estetycznie i trzeba sięgnąć po szczotkę.Po zastosowaniu wyżej wymienionego żelu na szczęście nie było tego efektu.Wieczorem bez problemu wyczesał się.Proste czy kręcone?Jestem posiadaczką prostych włosów i jak łatwo się domyśleć marzą mi się kręcone. Nie pozostaje mi nic innego jak  posiłkować się termolokami, wałkami, papilotami itp. Bardzo podobają mi się zarówno lekkie fale, jak i mocno skręcone loki. Jednak wyobrażam sobie ile trzeba wkładać czasu w ich ogarnięcie. Ja również nie budzę się z idealnie prostymi włosami. Tak jak pisałam na początku muszę suszyć, często je przeczesując i są proste jak druty. Jednak z tyłu w głębi naturalnie lekko falują i z nimi najciężej jest się uporać.Nie używam prostownicy, ale muszę się przyznać, że przedwczoraj wyciągnęłam ją z dna szafy. Często widzę na Instagramie Wasze piękne fale, które uzyskujecie za pomocą tego urządzenia i pozazdrościłam :) Ja uważam wszelkie prostownice, lokówki za zło, no ale wczoraj mnie podkusiło i.. nie nie to nie dla mnie. Nie umiem wyczarować pięknych fal i mam wrażenie, że lada moment a moje włosy się spalą :D  Od kiedy Zosia się urodziła opuściłam się mocno w pielęgnacji moich włosów. Ostatnio zdałam sobie sprawę, że ich stan pogorszył się. Częste suszenie, jak również farbowanie nie służy nikomu. Ale biorę się za siebie! Aktualnie używam świetnych kosmetyków do pielęgnacji- jestem z nich bardzo zadowolona. Zamówiłam swój ukochany olej Sesa i jak tylko dojdzie wracam do systematycznego olejowania, ponieważ to po nim moim zdaniem efekty są najlepsze.Koniecznie dajcie znać, jakie włosy podobają Wam się bardziej u siebie, u innych. Proste czy kręcone?

Monthly Empties | June, 2016. Ok, I know I'm a little late with the empties this month but since I finished up so many products I decided to do it late anyway. I don't know what it is about empties that get me so excited. Adding a new empty product to my little basket literally puts me in a good mood. I'm not even ashamed to admit it here because if you're reading this post that probably puts you in a good mood as well. Well, this month was a productive one. I managed to finish 10 products plus six MAC products that I had already backed-to-MAC before taking the pictures for this post so they won't be featured. But since I usually save my back-to-MAC products for months months before exchanging them it wouldn't be "fair" to put them with the rest anyway.Aside from the MAC products, I didn't finish any makeup items this month. It's mostly skin care, perfumes and some hair products. Still.. I'm excited. Like any beauty junkie I like rotating my products and knowing they are not just going bad in my cabinets. I've noticed that ever since I've started the blog and therefore the empties posts I've been more conscious of what I buy and also of what I'm actually able to use before it goes bad. So if you're having problems with that I guess starting a blog is a good solution!  TRESemmé Smooth & Straight Conditioner: TRESemmé is one of my favorite hair care brands. It's a good price, my hair likes it and it's easy to get. This is my go to conditioner. I like having options in the shower but I always have this one in the mix. I've repurchased it many times and I'll continue to do so. I like the scent and I feel like it keeps my hair healthy, specially now that I've gone a little lighter. Acetone: I do my nails at home so I usually go through a bottle of acetone every couple of months. It's cheap, easy to find and it takes the nail polish off in seconds. I know people say it's bad for the nails but my nails are just fine. I can't stand nail polish remover so I acetone it is.Physiogel Calming Lotion: I had a major skin problem-thing-allergy-reaction and these (and Cetaphil) were my best friends this month. I think it was eczema but I'm not sure because I didn't go to the doctor. I just applied moisturizer 3X a day and it did the trick. I would highly recommend this lotion if you have sensitive skin because this was a life saver. I was extremely moisturizing, it absorbed quickly in the skin and it helped a lot with the itching.Diesel Fuel For Life Eau de Parfum for Her: I cannot believe I finished a entire bottle of perfume. I think I've had this for 4 years or more but I wasn't even mad because I LOVE THIS SCENT. I'm not good at describing scent so I'm not even going to try. Next time you go to Sephora just try it and see if it's for you. As for the lasting power, it was pretty good. And also, keep in mind that I've had this for 4 years it didn't go bad.Bath & Body Works Fragrance Mist in Sweat Pea: This wasn't my favorite BBW scent and, honestly, I don't even know why I got it. This was a pain to use up. I get these fragrance mists because I like applying them everyday before class just to get a fresh and light scent so if I'm not a big fan of the scent you can see how it would be a pain to use up. But I guess that was my fault for choosing the wrong one. But in general, I love BBW fragrance mists.. Twilight Woods is the one I'm currently wearing and I would totally recommend trying it out. Sweat Pea? Not so much. Dove Beauty Bar: This is a staple in my bathroom. It's my favorite kind of soap. I love the smell, it's extremely moisturizing and it's relatively cheap. I use this in the shower and as a face wash every morning. I would recommend this to anyone, specially if you have dry or sensitive skin. Schwarzkopf Gliss Hair Repair Oil Elixir: I got this on a whim while I was traveling last year and it ended up being surprisingly good. This was the first Schwarzkopf product I've ever tried and now I really want to try more. I applied it after washing my hair and it made combing easier. It also helped with the frizz. It was good and I would consider buying it again but it wasn't a life changing thing.Granado Hand Cream in Pink: I love this hand cream but since it's a Brazilian brand I don't think it's easy to get it in other countries. It was one of those creams that moisturizes your hands but it doesn't leave them feeling greasy (which is surprisingly hard to find). If you ever manage to get your hands in Granado's products, go for this hand cream. Umiditá Lotion for Sensitive Skin: I've had this little sample around for months and I decided to pick it up and see if it would help me with my problem-thing-allergy-reaction. I'm not really sure if it did or not because there was so little of it and also because I was using so many different lotions at them time. So, I guess it was ok.Those are all the products I've finished up in June. Get ready for another big empties in July. I don't know what's going on but all my products are running out at the same time. I know.. It's weird but also GREAT. I love getting stuff out and making room for new products. And knowing that I got my money's worth out of a product is not bad either. If you've done an empties post or video lately let me know on the comments because I love reading/watching those. Like I said, empties put me in a good mood. I know.. I'm weird.Thanks so much for reading and I'll talk to you soon.

Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Conditioner Review Hello everyone!
Today’s review is about Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Conditioner. I always buy the shampoo and the corresponding conditioner together and also make sure that I use them together. I have seen that the results are better that way. I recently reviewed Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Shampoo and today I will be reviewing the conditioner. I was sold looking at the claims of the product. It states that the product will reduce hair breakage, claims to strengthen the hair 20 times more, and also to bring more luster to the hair. I was not really satisfied with the shampoo. Let us find out how this conditioner turned out to be.

Product Description:
The conditioner Glorious strengthens spoiled lifeless, weakened hair. The 3-way active conditioner formula is based on a combination of 3 proteins. These provide specific parts of the hair structure and strengthen the entire hair lengths. A real protein boost for stronger, glorious hair. Liquid Hair blocks reconstruct the hair and renew its quality. Hair damage can be repaired deep inside and on the hair surface.
Price:
€1.75 for 200ml/approximately 140 INR for 200ml
Ingredients:
Aqua, Cetearyl Alcohol, Quaternium-87, Stearamidopropyl Dimethylamine, Dimethicone, Distearoylethyl Hydroxyethylmonium Methosulfate, Isopropyl Myristate, Citric Acid, Hydrolyzed Keratin, Panthenol, Cocodimonium Hydroxypropyl Hydrolyzed Keratin, Glycerin, Propylene Glycol, Phenoxyethanol, Sodium Methylparaben, Parfum, Dimethiconol, Polyquaternium-10, Linalool, CI 15985, CI 16255
My Experience with Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Conditioner:
The packaging is very similar to other Gliss Kur shampoos. The color of the bottle is very catchy and attractive. It’s golden copper in color and I love it. The bottle also looks glossy. The bottle has a flap cap which opens and closes easily. The whole packaging is sturdy and leak-proof. The bottle also stands stable on the bathroom counter.

The conditioner itself is light blush in color. It’s a lovely color. It has a thick consistency. It’s very creamy and thick. When you apply it on wet hair, it kind of gets more liquidy making it easy to apply and also to spread. I use a coin size for my shoulder length hair. You can feel the hair detangling as you use the product. I wash it off with warm water and make sure that I don’t overwash my hair. To get best results, one needs to wash just the conditioner out and not more. The product also washes off very easily.

The fragrance is very nice and pretty strong. The fragrance also lasts for few hours. If you don’t prefer hair products with strong fragrance then stay away from it. Coming back to my impression about the product, I did not see any kind of improvement in my hair. My hair definitely felt softer and smoother and smelt great. But I could not see the “3 proteins” working for me. It’s just a normal conditioner.

Pros of Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Conditioner:
• Handy packaging
• Thick consistency
• Doesn’t weigh down the hair
• Strongly perfumed
• Leaves hair soft and smooth
• Detangles hair
Cons of Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Conditioner:
• Doesn’t strengthen hair
• Strong fragrance (not for all)
• Opaque bottle; difficult to know how much product is left
IMBB Rating:
4.5/5
Will I Repurchase Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Conditioner?
I love trying out new products so probably not. Also, it’s NOT the best conditioner I have tried.
Would I Recommend Schwarzkopf Gliss Kur Glorious Strengthening Conditioner?
Not really. Look for IMBB reviews and find a better one.

Banjara’s Milk Cream + Olive Super Soft Face Wash Review Skin type: Normal to oily
 Skin tone: Fair
Hello all!
As I mentioned in my earlier posts, I have hoarded lots of face washes; this one is one of them. Here’s a quick review.

Price:
INR 40 for 50ml

My Experience with Banjara’s Milk Cream + Olive Super Soft Face Wash:

I bought two variants of these face washes and I have been using them for over a month now. These sweaty summers have made me obsess over face washes. This one comes in a white tube with a bright green flip cap. Nothing special about the packaging: simple and functional. It is not bulky and can be carried around in purses and pouches. There are necessary details at the reverse side of the tube.

The face wash is milky white in color with a cream-like consistency. I can make out that it is pretty creamy by the looks of it. More or less, I can compare it to a lotion. It lather well too, upon contact with water. But I have noticed that it doesn’t rinse off completely. I feel a slimy layer on my skin still left behind even after rinsing. But after patting my face dry that doesn’t last. It feels a little weird.

It doesn’t dry out my skin or make it stretchy either. I can’t say it moisturizes my skin either but it effectively removes all the traces of oil and dirt from my face. It feels refreshing, but I have not noticed the marks on my chin and forehead fade because of this. Other than just cleansing effectively, it doesn’t do anything to solve skin problems. But then again, I haven’t actually come across one face wash that does. A pretty good face wash for the summers!
Pros of Banjara’s Milk Cream + Olive Super Soft Face Wash:
• Simple and user-friendly tube packaging.
• Travel-friendly.
• Nice, milky consistency.
• Feels creamy.
• Doesn’t make my skin dry and stretchy.
• Removes all traces of oil and dirt.
• Feels refreshing.
• Affordable.
Cons of Banjara’s Milk Cream + Olive Super Soft Face Wash:
• A slimy layer is left behind even after rinsing.
• Doesn’t do anything to even out skin tone or to reduce blemishes as claimed.
IMBB Rating:
3.8/5
Would I Recommend/Repurchase Banjara’s Milk Cream + Olive Super Soft Face Wash?
An average daily face wash, which doesn’t hurt the pocket much either. I’d only recommend it for the price. As I have two variants already, I don’t think I’ll be getting this again since I am not that impressed with this.

Schwarzkopf Essence Ultime Omega Repair Intensive Mask Review Hair type: Curly, but chemically straightened; shoulder length
Hello everyone!
Today’s review is about Schwarzkopf Essence Ultime Omega Repair Intensive Mask. This happens to be my first store-bought hair mask. We have all had our share with DIY hair masks especially with hair oil and so on. I also did it in the past. But now, due to shortage of time, getting to wash my hair twice a week is a big deal. I love the results when I apply hair oil, but oils aren’t always convenient. So, I thought of buying such hair masks. I got 2 of them and here is the review of the first product.

Product Description:
Discover truly beautiful hair with essence ULTÎME Omega Repair Intensive Mask. Luxurious Pearl Essence in a precious, nourishing formula that provides hair rebuild and split end prevention in 1 minute, developed with Claudia Schiffer.
Price:
€4.45 for 200ml/approximately 350 INR for 200ml
Ingredients:
Aqua, Cetearyl Alcohol, Isopropyl Myristate, Behentrimonium Chloride, Distearoylethyl Hydroxyethylmonium Methosulfate, Hydrolyzed Pearl, Plukenetia Volubilis Seed Oil, Panthenol, Cocodimonium Hydroxypropyl Hydrolyzed Keratin, Hydrolyzed Keratin, Maris Sal, Stearamidopropyl Dimethylamine, Cetyl Palmitate, Dimethicone, Citric Acid, Parfum, Phenoxyethanol, Isopropyl Alcohol, Methylparaben, Cetrimonium Chloride, Guar Hydroxypropyltrimonium Chloride, Glycerin, Hexyl Cinnamal, Linalool, Limonene, Benzyl Salicylate
My Experience with Schwarzkopf Essence Ultime Omega Repair Intensive Mask:

The packaging is very simple. It comes in a round plastic container with a cap. The container is white and gold in color. The packaging is sturdy and easy to hold and use. The cap of the container is a screw cap. So when you need to open or close, you need both your hands. The consistency of the product is creamy. The product itself is white in color. You need to directly dig in to the product and apply it on the wet hair. Since the product is very creamy, it’s easy to apply and spread all over the hair.

The fragrance is very mild and hard to describe. It’s a pleasant smell which most of us would like. It is recommended to use the product on wet hair for a minute and then wash off. The only way possible for me to use this was in the shower. I first shampooed my hair and then rinsed the shampoo. I always condition my hair after washing. But I wanted to see the results of the hair mask and skipped the conditioner. I applied the hair mask and let it work. Then, I rinsed off the hair mask with warm water. I then towel dried my hair. I could already see the results. My hair felt softer and more voluminous.

Once the hair was completely dry, it felt very soft, silky and smooth. The best part was that it felt very healthy and bouncy. My hair was not weighted down. The first time I used it, I got very excited and used 3 generous dollops After closing the lid, I started working with my hair and then realized that it was too much.The only con is the lid. I had to dump the product on my head and then close the lid and then massage the product into my hair. I also had to wash the container from outside since it got little dirty. Overall, I am very satisfied with the product. I guess I can replace my conditioner with this hair mask.

Swatch:

Pros of Schwarzkopf Essence Ultime Omega Repair Intensive Mask:
• Small, handy packaging
• Results are visible from first use
• Makes hair soft, silky and voluminous
• Doesn’t weigh the hair down
• Can be used in place of a conditioner
• Non-oily
• Lightly perfumed
Cons of Schwarzkopf Essence Ultime Omega Repair Intensive Mask:
• Packaging could have been better
IMBB Rating:
5/5
Would I Repurchase Schwarzkopf Essence Ultime Omega Repair Intensive Mask?
I love it. I couldn’t believe how silky and full of life my hair looked. I would also like to try other similar products from the same brand. But will stick to this variant until I find something better.
Would I Recommend Schwarzkopf Essence Ultime Omega Repair Intensive Mask?
Very much. This hair mask can do wonders. I would recommend it to everyone. You will love your hair like never before. You can see the results after one use.

Review del Aceite schwarzkopf Gliss con aceite de Argán Muy buenas!En un comentario me habéis pedido recientemente que haga alguna entrada de productos terminados. No suelo hacer este tipo de entradas porque me gusta que cada entrada hable solo de una cosa y no mezclar marcas y productos (manías mías porque luego sí que leo entradas de productos terminados de otra gente...).En fin, a lo que vamos, intentaré sacar más entradas con las cositas que voy terminando. Hoy le toca el turno al aceite de Schwarzkopf que acabo de terminar.Schwarzkopf Gliss con Aceite de ArganPrecio: 6-7€ / 75mlA la venta en supermercados y perfumeríasSe trata de un aceite para el cabello que hidrata y suaviza. Puede utilizarse sobre el cabello húmedo o seco y no necesita aclarado:La textura es de aceite denso y no deja sensación grasa sobre el pelo. Tiene el aroma característico de los productos de argán (tipo avainillado) y deja algo de rastro de olor en el pelo:Yo suelo salir de la ducha siempre con prisas, así que en lugar de acondicionador uso este tipo de aceites que no necesitan aclarado, y un día a la semana, cuando voy con más tiempo uso una mascarilla.Mi opiniónFué el primer aceite hidratante de cabello que utilicé, así que al principio me gustaba mucho. Siempre lo he utilizado tras el champú, con el cabello húmedo y sin aclarar. Deja el pelo suave y evita el encrespado, el pelo queda fácil de desenredar.Sin embargo desde entonces he probado muchos otros aceites, y el caso es que he probado otros de calidad similar o incluso mejor, con un precio bastante menor.Así que como conclusión, no creo que repita con este producto a no ser que lo vea de oferta, como a la mitad de precio...Quizá te interese:Muestras Gratis Junio 2016Lipmonthly por 4,5€Coloretes SleekSigueme y no te pierdas nada!!!

Top 3 Best And Worst Hair Dyes For Bright Colours | Hair I've been meaning to write this post for a while now, but I wanted to try a HUGE variety of hair dyes so I can fairly talk about my experience with the different dyes and share which I feel are the best dyes and also the worst. Since last summer I have been dip dying the ends of my hair, I have bleached it a few times during this period but I try to avoid bleaching it unless I have to. I've tried different colours and ranges from everywhere and taken up pretty much every single recommendation I've had. I have to say I have been trying this dye on bleached tips, and I have not been doing it on completely blonde hair so you may have a different experience to me. I have based the ranges on the lasting of the dye as well as the colour because obviously with me not having the lightest hair in the first place it would be unfair to judge it just on how it looked. The ones under the worst category aren't bad brands or anything like that I just found their colour to not last at all.WORST: 1. Crazy Colour:I honestly found this one of the worst for everything, I would apply it and within a few days it would completely have washed out, although I only wash my hair every other day within 3-4 washes it would all be gone, I found the worst colours for this orange and pink.2. Directions: I've heard people have good experiences with Directions but for me it was all bad, similar to the first dye but it hardly took at all, on freshly bleached hair I had to dye it three times for it work at all. Which isn't great for a dye, I have used them in the past and found similar problems then as well. For the price of one pot I expect a LOT better.3. XXL Schwarzkopf: I love their reds and they always take really well but any of their semi permanent dyes in fun colours I find wash out quickly and don't take to bleach well at all. Compared to the other two I liked them, and for the price I don't mind them, but they're not the best for getting those bright colours.BEST: 3. Manic Panic:Manic Panic have one of the prettiest colour ranges around, and although they come in little pots you don't need a lot to create a stir when it comes to beautiful fun colours. I love them for the variety of beautiful pinks and they tend to last fairly long and are cruelty free, win win.2. Stargazer: So Stargazer are hands down one of the best brands around, I have tried so many of their colours and they don't fade quickly and are long lasting, I love the purples which stargazer offer as even when they fade they turn into beautiful blues rather than gross green colours. For £5 honestly worth every penny.1. Colour Freedom:I am head over heels in love with this brand, for £6.99 you get the biggest bottle of colour and it's the best and long lasting one around. I love the fact that for £6.99 you get over 5 applications for dip dye and probably one or two full heads, you don't need a lot to cover a section and it looks bright and fun, even on darker hair. I love the fact it even when it fades it still looks fabulous.

London Drugs Annual Beauty Event - New Releases Preview! A couple of weeks ago I had the pleasure of attending London Drug's Annual Beauty event! This was the first time I was invited and I was very excited! We were taken by limo from downtown to a studio space where 16 vendors were set up to introduce us to the newest releases!I'll be reviewing a lot of the products in the upcoming months but wanted to share a quick overview of all the new items in this post!Almay: From the Age Essentials line, we were given the lip treatment, foundation, concealer and makeup wipes. The foundation looks super boring in the bottle but I've tried it once and really like it so far! It has medium coverage with a very weightless feel!Annabelle Cosmetics: New from Annabelle is a collection of mascaras to meet your every need! The most unique one is the Expandable Mascara which allows you to twist the wand to get the look you want. There are also some new lippies being released and I will be reviewing one next month.Calvin Klein: The classic Euphoria scent is spinning off a cousin: Deep Euphoria. The scent is floral and musky with top notes of cascalone and black magic rose. Samples were not available yet but looking forward to it!Conair: A new release is the Diamond Brilliance Ionic Straightening Brush. It combines a straightener and a hair brush in one. I tried it at the event and it made my hair feel silky and smooth. I'd really like to try this!e.l.f: I've been using elf products for a long time and still are using products from my huge haul 3 years ago. The samples include a face primer, blush and bronzing powder, matte eyeshadow palette, and contour palette. Essie: Okay I'm so excited about this! I love essie colors but always had a problem with their small brush. The new Gel Couture line up features WIDE brushes, yay! It almost covers my nail in one stroke and honestly I feel like the lasting power is better too. I've gotten minimal chipping and it's been 5 days. The old essie chips on me within 2 days! There are 42 shades available and I have Touch UpKiss: I've had a lot of experience with Kiss products but with nails or lashes. Their new makeup line up looks amazing. They had some seriously pigmented colorful eyeshadows. Unfortunately I didn't get any to try but keep your eyes out on the internet for swatches!Lise Watier: I actually missed the Lise Watier booth as it got too busy! One new product from them is the Twist & Sharp Automatic Long Lasting Eye Stylo that self sharpens!Makeup Revolution: I could not believe that Makeup Revolution was participating in this event! Canada never gets the cool brands! I first played with the brand in Ulta and was obsessed with the quality and pigmentation of their palettes. They'll be entering the Canadian market this fall at London Drugs! I'll be doing a full swatch and review on the 5 palettes I received. Neostrata: I've always seen Neostrata at stores but have never tried anything from them. They actually have quite a few cleansers and some really interesting ones like Cleansing Foaming Water and Detoxifying Micellar Gel. I'm currently trying to settle into a skincare routine so I might incorporate these products in the next couple of months. A product that will be available in September 2016 is the Pore Minimizer Anti-shine Hydrating Gel. I'm very interested to see how it would work.NYX: I feel like NYX is always releasing new products and I can't wait to try some of these. The lip cream is in the shade Vancouver!! And I'm obsessed with it. It's not very summer appropriate but it will be pulled out for the fall for sure! The London Drugs in downtown Vancouver has the biggest selection of NYX that I've seen. So definitely go browse the beauty department there if you are looking for NYX.OGX: I'm currently using the OGX Biotin set in my shower and love it! We checked out three new collections from OGX. There's the Strength & Body Bamboo + Fiber collection to help your hair appear fuller, thicker, and more voluminous. There's Fight Fallout + Niacin3 to exfoliate and stimulate your scalp. Lastly there's Gravity defying & Hydration which aims to a be an ultra lightweight formula.Revlon: I love it when drugstore brands come out with palettes! I've been using the Eyes, Cheeks + Lips palette and a full review will be coming soon. The Not just Nudes eyeshadow palette also has some gorgeous combinations of color. Lastly there's a new PhotoReady Insta-Fix Highlighting Stick and some new shades in the Ultra UD Matte Lipcolor.Sally Hansen: I've always been a fan of Sally Hansen's brush and polish formulas. They have a new Color Therapy range that is suppose to nourish your nails. I can't wait to try this as my nails peel all the time.Schwarzkopf: This will be my first time trying Schwarzkopf and the product they were featuring is the Biotin Volume set which was developed for fine, limp hair. Also I'm going to try and color my hair with the Keratin Color box dye which is almost odourless! StriVectin: Another brand that I've seen in stores but never tried. Their new products include the Multi Action Restorative Cream which fights 12 signs of aging. I might give this my mom to try. The other product I've already started using and quite like it! It's the Overnight Replenishing Moisture Mask and it gives a great boost of hydration.Youngblood: Lastly we have Youngblood which is a luxury mineral cosmetics line made for consumers looking for clean, natural products. Their most popular product is the Natural Mineral Foundation. Along with that we were given a concealer and a Mineral Mist.In addition to sampling so much makeup, it was a great time to catch up with friends I've made through beauty blogging including Whitney from Macarons and Mischief.So that was a huge post and I hope some of these items caught your eyes! Schnelle Auffrischung für die Haare - Batiste Trockenshampoo #blogthisway Wer kennt es nicht? Man muss los, aber die Haare sehen einfach nicht gut aus... ich habe euch schon ein Paar Mal von Trockenshampoo berichtet und probiere auch ab und an gerne mal neues aus. Aus diesem Grund freue ich mich, dass Batiste einer der Kooperationspartner unseres Bloggertreffens "Blog this Way" ist.TrockenshampootrendIn den letzten Jahren entdeckt man immer mehr Trockenshampoos in den Läden - viele namhafte Hersteller bieten ihre Produkte an, das war vor einigen Jahren noch nicht so: ich habe nach einem Trockenshampoo für Festivals gesucht und konnte nur das eine Produkt kaufen, was es gab. Es roch unangehehm und die Wirkung war auch nicht berauschend.Wozu Trockenshampoo?Na gut... es gibt nun also Trockenshampoo in Hülle und Fülle - aber man braucht ja nicht alles, was es gibt, oder?Festivals: Ein Paar Tage Festival sind ganz schön, aber nicht immer kann man dort vernünftig duschen oder die Haare waschen. Da kommt es dann ganz gelegen, wenn man mit Trockenshampoo mal eben die Haare auffrischen kann und sich einfach wohler fühlt.Pony: Abends die Haare gewaschen und morgens sieht der Pony völlig durcheinander aus - da hilft bei mir oft auch kämmen nichts. Schnell ein wenig Trockenshampoo und schon ist der Tag gerettet.Verschlafen: Eigentlich wollte man noch die Haare waschen... aber der Wecker hat einen nicht so früh geweckt, wie man wollte - zum Glück gibt es Trockenshampoo, denn nicht jeder Termin wartet auf einen.Mit Haaröl verhauen: man möchte Abends weg gehen, ist schon fast fertig, jetzt noch das neue glitzernde Haaröl verwenden... Mist, das war einfach zu viel! Auch bei diesem Unfall habe ich schonmal meine Haare mit Trockenshampoo gerettet - mal eben waschen und wieder trocken föhnen ist bei meiner Länge einfach nicht drin, wenn ich eh schon los möchte.Einen Tag mehr ohne Waschen: das kann selbstverständlich auch ein Grund sein, um Trockenshampoo zu nutzen - dafür wurde es gemacht.Wie ihr seht kann Trockenshampoo vielseitig eingesetzt werden, vorausgesetzt man hat die richtige Sorte für sich gefunden.Batiste TrockenshampooDie Trockenshampoos von Batiste gibt es in verschiedenen Varianten, für unser Treffen haben wir aus der Reihe mit Duft bekommen. Es gibt auch noch Reihen mit Farbpigmenten und mit Stylingeffekt.Das schreibt Batiste auf der Homepage:Batiste ist die Trockenshampoo Marke Nr. 1* in UK und gehört zu den Trendprodukten in der Haarkosmetik – Internationale Stars lieben Batiste!Batiste ist ein ehemaliges Markenzeichen der Firma Schwarzkopf und wurde bereits 1970 entwickelt.2010  wurde die Marke Batiste von dem Unternehmen Church & Dwight Co.  Inc. aus Großbritannien übernommen. Seitdem wird die Marke erfolgreich  weiterentwickelt, um den Verbraucherbedürfnissen einerseits und  aktuellen Trends andererseits zu entsprechen. Das Ergebnis dieser  Strategie: Batiste ist mittlerweile in über 68 Ländern weltweit  erhältlich!Wie ihr schon auf den Bildern erkennen konntet habe ich die Sorte "tropical" ausprobiert. Die Reaktion von meinem Freund als er ins Bad kam war nicht wie sonst bei Trockenshampoo "iiihhhh" sondern "hier riecht es aber gut!" und genau das macht Batiste Trockenshampoos vor allem für mich aus: der gute Duft, den man sogar wählen kann.Folgende Düfte könnt ihr bekommen: oriental, original, blush, cherry, tropical, freshGenauere Infos zu den Düften findet ihr hier auf der Homepage.Auch praktisch: viele Sorten sind nicht nur in der 200ml Variante erhältlich, sondern auch in der praktischen 50ml Variante zum Probieren oder für unterwegs. Die 50ml Variante gefällt mir sehr gut, man schmeißt ja ungern etwas weg, was einem vom Duft her nicht so zusagt oder dessen Wirkung nicht so überzeugend ist - bei diese Variante wird es einem einfacher gemacht, das Produkt eventuell doch noch aufzubrauchen, oder einfach Platz zu sparen.Die AnwendungAus 30cm Entfernung aufsprühen, einmassieren, auskämmen, fertig. Das geht schnell und ist sehr einfach.Die WirkungNicht jedes Trockenshampoo funktioniert bei jedem, bei manchen Haaren funktioniert auch einfach gar kein Trockenshampoo. Ich habe sehr feines, helles Haar und kann euch ein kleines Ergebnis nutzen für eine Anwendung, die ich öfter nutze: der nicht mehr so schöne Pony.Auf dem Foto sehr ihr mein Pony, links: vorher - rechts: nachher.Beim Greifen in die Haare merkt man eventuell noch Rückstände vom Produkt, das stört im Normalfall aber nicht. Der gute Duft und die Wirkung sind es wert und auch der Preis von ca. 3,99-4,99€ (je nach Sorte) für 200ml oder 1,79€ sind völlig in Ordnung.Batiste Trockenshampoos könnt ihr beispielsweise bequem bei Amazon oder Douglas bestellen.FazitNach meiner ersten Erfahrung mit den Batiste Trockenshampoos habe ich diese im Hinterkopf als okay in der Wirkung und super vom Duft her (damals hatte ich die Cherry Variante). Nach ein Paar Anwendungen bin ich mit den Ergebnissen zufrieden und könnte mir vorstellen Trockenshampoo von Batiste öfter zu nutzen und nachzukaufen, wenn mein anderes Produkt aufgebraucht ist. Wer Sorten von anderen Herstellern vom Duft her nicht mag könnte bei Batiste gut fündig werden und mit den 50ml Varianten Geld beim Probieren sparen.Nutzt ihr auch ab und an Trockenshampoo? Wie gefallen euch die Düfte?Liebe Grüße,Annika

Glossybox Mai "Classy Queen" Ich möchte heute euch die neue Glossybox zeigen. Eigentlich wollte ich sie nicht weil ich sie nicht mag aber dank brand4friends hab ich mir eine weitere Box aufzwingen lassen. Es gab nämlich im Monat April ein tolles Angebot. Für 5€ eine Glossybox. Natürlich denkt man, ey geil anstatt für 15€ nur 5€ und dann meistens ein Warenwert zwischen 40-60€. Dabei dachte ich, das ich auch eine aktuelle bekomme und keine 0815 Box. Das Problem ist das ich alle Artikel schon hatte die da drin waren weil ich 1 Jahr mal die Glossybox getestet habe (deswegen bin ich zum Entschluss gekommen nie wieder eine zu bestellen). Naja ,nun gut waren ja immerhin nur 5€.Doch leider hat die Glossybox eine nicht so schöne Kündigungsfrist und ich habe auch erst gekündigt als ich meine Brand4friends Box bekommen habe, da ich sicher sein wollte. Ja schön und dann lese ich das ich noch die Mai Box bekomme. Naja, egal hier ist sie :  Ich war wie immer nicht dolle überrascht. Ich kenne das ja schon alles. Das Thema ist Classy Queen. Ich finde das Thema  GÄÄÄÄÄHN, Langweilig.   Für  die eine ist es ein ebenmäßiger Teint mit zartem Blush, für die  andere sind es rote Lippen und glamouröse Hairstyles. Für uns ist  eine CLASSY QUEEN jede Frau, die sich einfach wohl in ihrer Haut  fühlt. Genau dafür gemacht sind die wunderbaren Beauty- und  Pflege-Highlights dieser Box!  Die Produkte in meiner Box sind eigentlich sehr gut gemischt. Es ist alles dabei: Mascara,Nagellack,Reinigung,Haare und was fürs Gesicht. Die Marken sind, naja, ich sag jetzt mal OK. Ich weiß nicht aber irgendwie finde ich die Boxen immer etwas langweilig. Aber ok für mich ist die Glossybox ja eh nichts. Es sind 5 Produkte vorhanden, diesmal sogar alle in Originalgröße, bis auf 1 Produkt. Sonst sind meistens Probiergrößen dabei was ich damals immer kritisiert habe. Aber die Preise für ein paar Produkte , deren Marken unbekannt sind finde ich etwas happig. Aber man soll ja nicht so voreilig sein. Erst testen dann meckern :D Ich habe mir auch bei der Glossybox immer gewünscht mehr Marken die man kennt mit rein zupacken. Natürlich kommt man nicht drumherum und es sind immer Marken dabei die man nicht kennt. Finde ich auch voll ok. In dieser Box sind 3 Marken drin die nicht so bekannt sind und 3 Marken die jeder kennt. Ich hab zwar gesagt bzw. geschrieben Marken die man kennt aber keine Drogerie Produkte :D  Ich dachte eher an tolle Marken. Müssen ja jetzt nicht so teuer sein. In dem Magazin finde ich Z.b.: Neutrogena ganz toll oder Mary Kay !! Aber leider waren die natürlich nicht in meiner Box drin. (Wie Immer!!) Ich habe auch gelesen das fast jeder diese Box bekommen hat wie ich und wenige die Box mit Mary Kay. Dann stell ich euch mal die tollen Produkte vor. icona Milano Emotion Allowed 16,50 €                                / 10 ml (Originalgröße)Drama,  Baby! Mit dieser lang anhaltenden, paraben- und tierversuchsfreien  Mascara in Tiefschwarz sind Emotionen Pflicht. Im Handumdrehen  gelingt ein ausdrucksstarkes Augen-Make-up dank der dermatologisch  getesteten, cremigen Formulierung und der Bürste, die dramatisches  Volumen mit Fächereffekt kreiert. Und falls es doch mal zu  emotional wird, kein Problem: Die Tusche ist wasserresistent.Die Marke kenne ich schon durch einer Glossybox. Bin nicht begeistert und ich habe sie auch schon getestet und finde sie sooo schlimm. -.- Bericht dazu folgt noch mit Bildern usw.Unani Dermo Defense Face Mask   15,99 €                                / 100ml (Originalgröße)    Man kombiniere gründliche Reinigung mit reichhaltiger Pflege und  wirksamem Schutz in einer Maske und herauskommt die Dermo Defense Face  Mask. Sie befreit das Gesicht von Unreinheiten, nährt, regeneriert und  bewahrt es vor schädlichen Umwelteinflüssen. Extraplus für  Umweltbewusste: Das Produkt ist biologisch abbaubar und nicht an Tieren  getestet. Diese Marke kenne ich nicht und ich mag auch keine unbekannten Marken wie oben schon erwähnt. Ich mag zwar eher Tuchmasken zu benutzten aber ich werde sie trotzdem mal ausprobieren. Vom Design her zieht mich die Tube nicht an.Catrice Ultimate Nail Lacquer 108  The Very Berry Best 2,79 €                                / 10 ml (Originalgröße)    Ganz klar, die Entscheidung fällt natürlich auf „The Very Berry Best“.  Und zwar für den formaldehyd- und phthalatfreien Nagellack im satten  Beerenton. Seine deckende Textur überzeugt, seine lange Haltbarkeit  beeindruckt und seine einzigartige Farbbrillanz verführt. Was bleibt,  sind perfekt manikürte Hände, um unmissverständliche Statements zu  setzen.                            Mhm, ja also Catrice ist eigendlich ok aber irgendwie finde ich es zu langweilig! Die Farbe ist ja schön aber für mich nichts da ich schon unendlich viele Nagellacke habe in der Farbe.   Schwarzkopf FIBREPLEX No.3 Bond Maintainer 21,50 €                                / 100 ml (Originalgröße)    Die innovative Intensivkur ist ein verlässlicher Power-Partner beim  Haarefärben. Dank der einzigartigen  „Fibre Bond“-Technologie ist die Mähne ab sofort schon beim Färben  geschützt. Finde ich super ! Mit Hyaluronsäure und  Algenextrakt versetzt, glättet sie Trockenheitslinien und -fältchen. Der  Teint erscheint frischer und praller. Für eine ebenmäßige, strahlende  Haut. Finde ich ok aber bin nicht so super begeistert. Wieder eine Marke die ich nicht kenne. Werde ich demnächst ausprobieren. Vielleicht kann sie ja was ;)  NIVEA Creme Pflege Reinig

Babyliss no cabelo médio! Desde que cortei o cabelo muita gente tem me perguntado como faço para arrumar o cabelo médio – vocês sabem que eu amo um babyliss e continuo fazendo quase todos os dias, mesmo com o comprimento mais curto. O babyliss agora é um pouco diferente: se por um lado demora bem menos tempo, por outro pode ser mais trabalhoso, principalmente nas mechas de trás. O meu objetivo quando arrumo o meu cabelo agora é algo assim:

Esses cabelos são todos obra do Anh Co Tran (que eu fiquei chamando de ela um bom tempo kkk), um cabeleireiro estrelado de Beverly Hills (quero passar no salão dele quando voltar a LA!) que foi a minha maior inspiração ao cortar. Os cortes são quase sempre em camadas (como o meu), o que dá um movimento lindo quando está sob o efeito do babyliss.

Enquanto não consigo um horário com ele, me viro com duas ferramentas: o miracurl e o babyliss normal. Parece pouco prático, mas não é: como as mechas da parte mais de trás da cabeça são curtinhas, não consigo fazer um babyliss bem feito, me atrapalho toda! Então uso o miracurl no cabelo todo e deixo as duas mechas mais da frente da cabeça pra fazer com o babyliss normal, que acho que dá um acabamento mais bonito. Nessas mechas da frente eu tento deixar a ponta reta, como o Anh faz, acho mais moderno. Uso dois produtos pra isso: um protetor termal (adoro o da Chi) e um spray finalizador (ando usando um da linha Osis da Schwarzkopf).
O processo todo dura uns oito minutos, kkk! Bem menos tempo do que eu gastava quando o cabelo estava compridão, e olha que troco de aparelho no meio ;D
Quem quiser aprender a fazer babyliss pode dar uma olhada nesses vídeos (antigão!) do canal:

Schwarzkopf Got2B Twisted Curling Mousse Review Hair type: Curly, but chemically straightened; shoulder length
Hello everyone!
Today’s review is about Schwarzkopf Got2B Twisted Curling Mousse. Recently, I was cleaning my cupboard and found this product hidden somewhere deep inside. It brought back the memories I had with my curly hair. I would use this product regularly to get those perfect curls. I do miss my curly look, but I like the straight hair look for now. So I thought of reviewing this product and letting you guys know how good it is. When I had curly hair, I always found it hard to find curly hair styling products, which made me dislike my hair. But Schwarzkopf Got2B is one such brand which caters to curly hair. This product added so much fun to the boring curly hair I had.

Product Description:
Boost your bounce and kick your curls into shape! NEW got2b twisted curling mousse with double curling power defines your locks + controls frizz. Say goodbye to uncontrolled styles and hello to endless definition and shine!
Price:
€2.75 for 250ml/approximately 200 INR for 250ml
Ingredients:
Aqua, VP/VA Copolymer, Butane, Propane, Polyquaternium-11, Sodium Benzoate, Cetrimonium Chloride, Isobutane, Panthenol, Amodimethicone, Tocopheryl Acetate, PEG-40 Hydrogenated Castor Oil, Hydroxyethylcellulose, Limonene, Lactic Acid, Cyclomethicone, Phenoxyethanol, Citric Acid, Trideceth-12, Caprylyl Glycol, Parfum, Pantolactone, Linalool
My Experience with Schwarzkopf Got2B Twisted Curling Mousse:

The packaging of the product is fun and colorful. It is catchy pink in color. The product comes in a tin tube with a spray dispenser. It looks very much like a deodorant bottle but is a little bit bigger. On the top, is a nozzle which dispenses the mousse. It’s very easy to use and one can easily control the amount of product dispensed too. The packaging is sturdy and travel safe. The mousse itself is white in color and has a good firm consistency. It spreads well in the hair and is easy to use.

I would normally start by shampooing and then wiping my hair with a towel. The product works better with slightly wet hair. I would then take a lemon sized portion of the mousse and apply it from the roots to the tips. I would usually work with small portions as they are easy to handle. Once you are done with application of the mousse, you need to scrunch the hair in upward movement. You can use a hair dryer with a diffuser (optional) to slightly dry the hair. Don’t be scared in using more product if required. Once your hair is slightly dry, you need to scrunch the hair once again with your hands and let it air dry. I would never use a comb (during or after styling) as it would spoil the whole look.

Working on slightly wet hair helps in binding the curls well. The product can also be used on dry hair but I have never tried it because I feel it doesn’t provide best results. Doing all of the above will result in cute, bouncy curls. The product also reduces frizzy hair and also provides extra shine to hair. The extra shine makes the hair look healthier.

Pros of Schwarzkopf Got2B Twisted Curling Mousse:
• Handy packaging
• Spray nozzle is well designed
• Brings curls back to shape
• Reduces frizz
• Effective in keeping curls in shape
• Non-sticky and non-oily
• Does not weigh down hair
• Smells great
• Makes hair shiny
Cons of Schwarzkopf Got2B Twisted Curling Mousse:
• Suitable for curly hair only
IMBB Rating:
5/5
Would I Repurchase Schwarzkopf Got2B Twisted Curling Mousse?
This is the best curling product I have owned. I don’t use it anymore since my hair is chemically straightened. But, if I ever go back to my good old curly look, this is the first product I will buy.
Would I Recommend Schwarzkopf Got2B Twisted Curling Mousse?
If you struggle with curly hair and don’t know how to style it, go for this product. It creates and holds those beautiful curls. You will fall in love with your hair.

Mes derniers achats beauté Hellooooooo les filles Tout d abord, désolée pour mon absence, j'ai été pas mal occupée d'un point de vue privé.Promis, j'essaie de reprendre les articles de manière plus régulière !! Je vous retrouve aujourd'hui pour vous parler des quelques petits achats que j'ai fait ce matin !! Je me suis rendue dans l'enseigne Trafic et je suis repartie avec 4 achats beauté sous le bras, J'avais envie de les partager avec vous, et de vous donner mes premières impressions.En détail:Pour commencer, j'ai pris une coloration de la gamme Poly Palette, de chez Schwarzkopf, a moins de 5euros. Comme je l'ai déjà dit une bonne centaine de fois je crois, je fais moi même ma coloration à la maison, la dernière que j'ai faite était un chocolat avec des reflets acajou... Et ici j'ai repris un simple noir, basique, simple et efficace !!    Ensuite, j'ai pris ce gel douche de la marque Cottage, j'aime énormément leurs gels douche qui sentent divinement bon, et laisse la peau douce, hydratée et parfumée! Je voulais tester depuis un sacré bout de temps celui-là à la cerise noire & pistache, introuvable jusqu'ici, j'ai été super contente de tomber dessus ce matin, les formats de 250 ml sont vendus un peu plus de 2euros dans cette enseigne.   ﻿J'ai également pris ce masque à l'argile de la marque Evoluderm, marque que je ne connaissais pas du tout. Mais étant donné que j'ai toujours entendu que du positif en ce qui concerne les bienfaits de l'argile pour la peau, je me suis laissée tenter par celui-ci. Il m'a couté moins de 3euros. Une fois rentrée, je me suis démaquillée et j'ai appliqué le masque et je l'ai laissé poser entre 5 et 6 minutes ... le résultat est juste BLUFFANT!!! Je suis hyper satisfaite! J'avais pas mal de points noirs sur la pointe du nez et sur les ailes du nez également et une fois le masque enlevé, plus RIEN ! Il est génial ce produit !! Promis je vous en parlerai plus longuement dans un prochain article! Et on termine par un achat makeup, un anticernes de la marque Glam Up, shoppé pour moins de 4 euros, en teinte 01. Vous savez que j aime beaucoup tester les anticernes, dès que j'en trouve a prix raisonnable je les achète ... on verra ce que ça donne niveau tenue, application, texture ... je vous en reparle bientôt également.  ﻿  Voila mes jolies, j'en ai terminé en ce qui concerne mes petits achats du jour. N'hésitez pas à me laisser un petit commentaire ici ou sur les réseaux sociaux pour me dire ce que vous pensez de ces produits si vous avez eu l'occasion de les tester ;) Je vous embrasse et je vous souhaite une belle soirée et vous dis à très bientôt !! Yasmine <3﻿

Allerdings komme ich eher selten zu Rossmann und die anderen Läden sind relativ weit weg, weshalb diese LE wohl an mir vorbeigehen wird, falls sie noch doch nachträglich noch bei dm erscheint :D Wie gefallen euch die Produkte?
